{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14942"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14942"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.13,0.16,0.13,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7630"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18668"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMeasles virus infection causes significant immune suppression that can persist for several weeks after the initial infection. The virus enters immune cells through the CD150 (SLAM) receptor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following immune cells is primarily suppressed during measles virus infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T cells","B cells","Macrophages","Dendritic cells","Neutrophils"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe measles virus primarily targets and suppresses \u003Cstrong\u003ET cells\u003C/strong\u003E, leading to lymphopenia and decreased cell-mediated immunity. This occurs because T cells highly express the CD150 (SLAM) receptor, which the virus uses to enter cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other immune cells are less affected:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB cells\u003C/strong\u003E can be impacted but are not the primary target\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrophages\u003C/strong\u003E participate in the immune response but are not specifically suppressed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E may be infected but are not the main target of suppression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E remain largely functional during measles infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe consequences of T cell suppression include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDirect infection and destruction of T cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EImpaired T cell proliferation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESuppressed cell-mediated immunity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased susceptibility to secondary infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Measles virus causes immune suppression primarily by depleting T cells and impairing their function through the CD150 receptor.","Immune suppression by measles can last for several weeks after infection, increasing susceptibility to other infections.","T cells are the primary target of measles virus, leading to lymphopenia and decreased cell-mediated immunity."],"references":["de Vries RD, Mesman AW, Geijtenbeek TB, Duprex WP, de Swart RL. The pathogenesis of measles. Curr Opin Virol. 2012 Jun;2(3):248-55. doi: 10.1016/j.coviro.2012.03.005. Epub 2012 Apr 5. PMID: 22483507.","Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14942"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T09:59:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T10:00:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7630"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66461"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":